Case Study Unit 15 - Unlabeled Dataset Modeling and Prediction¶

Yao Yao, Ivelin Angelov, Brian Kruse

MSDS 7333 Section 402

August 20, 2018

Introduction¶

An unlabeled dataset is applied ensemble categorical prediction methods to find the best accuracy and ROC score. Lesser features from random forest are removed and optimal parameters are found by gridsearch. Depending on customer needs, ROC score, accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-Score are all calculated as metrics to focus on true positive over false positive rate, correct predictions, true positives, false negatives, or the balance between true positives and false negatives. For the purposes of this study, ROC score and precision are used.

Methods¶

The steps used for this analysis were: data exploration, conversion of categorical data into dummy numerical variables, filling in missing values with the mean, application of categorical prediction, removal of lesser features, random forest parameter gridsearch, and finding the model with best ROC score, accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-Score.

colnames=list(df.drop(['y'], axis=1).select_dtypes(exclude='O').columns.values)
for i in colnames[0:]:
    if pd.notnull(i):
        mean = df[i].mean()
        df[i] = df[i].fillna(mean)
In [13]:
colnames=list(df.select_dtypes(include='O').columns.values)
for i in colnames[0:]:
    # Fill missing data with the word "Missing"
    df[i].fillna("Missing", inplace=True)
    # Create array of dummies
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[i], prefix=i)
    # Update X to include dummies and drop the main variable
    df = pd.concat([df, dummies], axis=1)
    df.drop([i], axis=1, inplace=True)

Predictions¶

The dataset is scaled from 1 to 0 so that the later removal of lesser features are not influenced by the numeric range of the variables. The training and test set are separated with a 4:1 ratio with random state of 2. The get_metrics function finds the ROC score, accruacy, precision, recall, and F1 Score.

In [15]:
y = df.pop('y')

columns = df.columns
sc = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
df = sc.fit_transform(df)
df = pd.DataFrame(df, columns=columns)

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=2)

def get_metrics(y_true, y_pred, treshhold=.5):
    y_pred = (y_pred > treshhold).astype(np.int32)
    return dict(
        RocAuc="{:.4f}".format(metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)),
        Accuracy="{:.4f}".format(metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)),
        Precision="{:.4f}".format(metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred)),
        Recall="{:.4f}".format(metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred)),
        F1="{:.4f}".format(metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred))
    )

With binary classification, logistic regression, decision tree classifier, and random forest classifier are selected. Logistic regression has a ROC score of 0.67 and a precision of 0.67; decision tree classifier has a ROC score of 0.84 and a precision of 0.81; random forest classifier has a ROC score of 0.87 and a precision of 0.92. Accuracy, recall, and F1-Score metrics also are calculated.

Conclusion¶

Depending on customer needs, ROC score, accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-Score are all calculated as metrics to focus on correct predictions, true positives, false negatives, or the balance between true positives and false negatives. For the best binary predictor, random forest with min samples split as 3, max features as log2, and criterion as entropy are the best hyperparameters. The removal of lesser features reduced overfitting and increased the ROC score and accuracy of the prediction. Setting the number of estimators as 1000 further increased the final metrics, where ROC score is 0.9390, accuracy is 0.9440, precision is 0.9457, recall is 0.9134, and F1-score is 0.9293. Further information from the original dataset is needed for which metric emphasis is needed to tune the parameters to satisfy customer needs.
